    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 2.76,
      "end": 4.66,
      "text": "All LibraVox recordings are in the public domain.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 5.62,
      "end": 9.5,
      "text": "For more information or to volunteer, go to LibraVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 10.5,
      "end": 13.5,
      "text": "This recording is by Mark Smith of Simpsonville, South Carolina.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 15.46,
      "end": 16.32,
      "text": "ESOP's Fables.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 17.36,
      "end": 18.44,
      "text": "The Clown and the Countryman.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 19.92,
      "end": 24.82,
      "text": "A nobleman announced his intention of giving a public entertainment in the theater, and",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 24.82,
      "end": 29.12,
      "text": "offered splendid prizes to all who had any novelty to exhibit at the performance.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 30.18,
      "end": 35.6,
      "text": "The announcement attracted a crowd of conjurers, jugglers, and acrobats, and among the rest",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 35.6,
      "end": 40.44,
      "text": "a clown, very popular with a crowd, who let it be known that he was going to give an",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 40.44,
      "end": 41.52,
      "text": "entirely new turn.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-011",
      "start": 42.36,
      "end": 47.18,
      "text": "When the day of the performance came, the theater was filled from top to bottom some",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-012",
      "start": 47.18,
      "end": 48.88,
      "text": "time before the entertainment began.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-013",
      "start": 49.74,
      "end": 55.92,
      "text": "Several performers exhibited their tricks, and then the popular favorite came on empty",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-014",
      "start": 55.92,
      "end": 57.06,
      "text": "handed and alone.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-015",
      "start": 57.82,
      "end": 63.32,
      "text": "At once there came a hush of expectation, and he, letting his head fall upon his breast,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-016",
      "start": 64.14,
      "end": 69.2,
      "text": "imitated the squeak of a pig to such perfection that the audience insisted on his producing",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-017",
      "start": 69.2,
      "end": 74.44,
      "text": "the animal, which, they said, he must have somewhere concealed about his person.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-018",
      "start": 75.02,
      "end": 81.04,
      "text": "He, however, convinced them that there was no pig there, and then the applause was deafening.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-019",
      "start": 82.32,
      "end": 88.38,
      "text": "Among the spectators was a Countryman, who disparaged the clown's performance, and announced",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-020",
      "start": 88.38,
      "end": 93.0,
      "text": "that he would give a much superior exhibition of the same trick on the following day.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-021",
      "start": 93.86,
      "end": 98.92,
      "text": "Again the theater was filled to overflowing, and again the clown gave his imitation amidst",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-022",
      "start": 98.92,
      "end": 100.18,
      "text": "the cheers of the crowd.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-023",
      "start": 100.18,
      "end": 106.76,
      "text": "The Countryman, meanwhile, before going on the stage, had secreted a young porker under",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-024",
      "start": 106.76,
      "end": 113.4,
      "text": "his smock, and when the spectators derisively bade him do better, if he could, he gave it",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-025",
      "start": 113.4,
      "end": 115.8,
      "text": "a pinch in the ear and made it squeal loudly.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-026",
      "start": 116.62,
      "end": 121.58,
      "text": "But they all with one voice shouted out that the clown's imitation was much more true to",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-027",
      "start": 121.58,
      "end": 121.84,
      "text": "life.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-028",
      "start": 122.78,
      "end": 128.9,
      "text": "Thereupon he produced the pig from under his smock and said, sarcastically, there, that",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-029",
      "start": 128.9,
      "end": 135.6,
      "text": "shows what sort of judges you are, and of Esau's fables, the clown and the Countryman.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
